      "content": "The American economic structure is not a meritocracy; it is a deeply entrenched system rigged by centuries of racial oppression that has systematically denied wealth accumulation to Black and Brown Americans. To claim that the current disparities are merely the result of individual choices is a willful blindness to the structural violence embedded in our financial institutions. Therefore, wealth redistribution is not a radical proposal, but a fundamental moral imperative required to dismantle a system designed to perpetuate racial hierarchy.\n\nThe first pillar of this argument must be the undeniable legacy of discriminatory policy. Policies like redlining and unequal access to capital were not accidental oversights; they were deliberate governmental actions that starved minority communities of the foundational assets—property and savings—necessary for generational wealth building. This historical theft has created a permanent economic chasm, meaning that simply \"leveling the playing field\" is impossible when one side started the race miles behind due to state-sanctioned theft.",
